items.description:
The woodcut showing 'Luther as Junker Jörg' is the last graphic portrait of Luther by Cranach. and marked his return to the public stage in 1522. It was widely disseminated and continued to be printed until late into the 16th century. The inscription celebrates Luther's return employing the island of Patmos (where St John wrote the Apocalypse) as a metaphor for his time at the Wartburg.
This edition must have appeared before Luther's final return to Wittenberg, to which allusion is made in the second edition. In the first edition there is no break in the outline of the right shoulder.
[Dodgson 1911, 317]
items.inscription:
Top: 'Luthcrus'
Below:
Quesitus toties, toties tibi Rhoma petitus/En ego per Christum viuo Lutherus adhuc/ Vna mihi spes est, quo non fraudabor, Iesus/ Hunc mihi dum teneam, perfida Rhoma vale.
items.markings: Hand and text written in red chalk in margin

additionalTextInformation.text:
Two editions of the woodcut. The earlier reproduced by Lippmann is in Dresden; fine impression with broad margins; sheet size: 442 x 312; old inscription in verse, in red chalk, running round the woodcut. It has above the portrait only the name ‘Lutherus’ (sic), and beneath it the four verses´, with different orthography. This edition must have appeared before Luther’s final return to Wittenberg, to which allusion is made in the second edition. In the first edition there is no break in the outline of the r. shoulder.
[Dodgson 1911, 317]

An early print in the Prints and Drawing Department in Dresden, which only has the name 'Lutherus' above the portrait and below the two couplets: Quaesitus-vale. 
[Schuchardt 1871,vol. III, 254, No. 179]

titles.title: Double Portrait of the Electors Friedrich III the Wise and Johann the Steadfast of Saxony

items.dimensions:
Sheet: 13.2 x 11.8 cm
[Kupferstichkabinett, Berlin, revised 2018]
items.description:
Portrait of Elector Friedrich the Wise and his brother Duke Johann the Steadfast of Saxony; in half-length, standing under an arch behind a ledge; two coats of arms in the upper corners.
This engraving served as the title-page to the second edition of the Wittenberg Heiligthumsbuch. This impression exhibits an impression of Cranach's woodcut of the church of All Saints printed on the verso (Hollstein, 96), but the book title in letter print has not survived.
items.signature: Artist's insignia on the ledge: serpent with elevated wings, facing right and dated '1510'

additionalTextInformation.text:
Cranach engraved two earlier portraits of Friedrich the Wise (1463-1525). One shows him kneeling in adoration of St Bartholomew (c. 1508-9) and in the other, dated 1509, he is seen within a similar arch with some of the background hatched and some left blank. The unfinished appearance of the latter engraving indicates that it may be a preliminary idea for the title-page to the Heiligthumsbuch, before it was decided to represent the Elector with his brother. 
These portrait engravings predate the first engraved portrait by Dürer, that of Cardinal Albrecht of Brandenburg of 1519. Dürer's engraving served as the title-page of the Hallesche Heiligthumsbuch, published in Halle in 1520, and the designs of the woodcut illustrations in it by Dürer's pupil Wolf Traut were much influenced by Cranach's designs for the Wittenberg Heiligthumsbuch.

items.description:
This is the only surviving impression of this woodcut, which suggests a limited print run and moreover reflects the fact that this print could also be used. The sheet could be employed as a sundial if it was aligned correctly with the assistance of a gnomon positioned over the central circle. In addition to the time of day an informed user could calculate the times of the sunrise and sunset with the astronomical chart arranged around the edge. Framed by knights the influence of the planets on mankind¿s activity is illustrated in the centre. Below the arts of sculpture and painting are shown beneath the planet Mercury. [..] Elector Friedrich the III¿s coats of arms are shown in a prominent position above. The mathematician Bonifatius Rode von Zörbig is the intellectual creator of the woodcut.
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, No. 54]

titles.title: Luther as an Augustinian Friar in a Niche

items.dimensions:
Sheet: 16.5 x 11.5 cm
[http://sammlungenonline.albertina.at/?query=Inventarnummer=[DG1929/80]&showtype=record]
items.description:
Cranach created the first realistic portrait of Luther. The court painter was inspired by Dürer's portrait of Albrecht, Cardinal of Brandenburg to create this etching. Luther is shown in three quarter profile, facing left. The habit and tonsure identify him as an Augustinian monk, and his facial expression reveals his determination and strong willpower. 
[...] An altered version of the earlier print [CDA:G_AT_A_DG1929-78] shows Luther as a half-length figure with hands. He grasps a closed book in his right hand and holds his left hand in front of his body. The reformer is shown in a niche and his face appears milder and more soulful. It was the first official portrait of Luther and frequently copied by artists in subsequent years.
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, 190, No. 94]

titles.title: Luther as an Augustinian Friar with Cap

items.dimensions:
Sheet: 20.9 x 15 cm
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, No. 95]
items.description:
Cranach completed this second engraved portrait of Luther in 1521 before the Reichstag in Worms. This portrait has survived in a number of states. Shown as a bust-length figure this strict profile of Luther ranks it in the tradition of ruler portraits on coins and medallions. Luther is shown wearing a habit, but on this occasion instead of a tonsure he now wears a cap pushed to the back of his head, identifying him as an academic doctor. In contrast with the works from 1520 Luther appears less ascetic and considerably plumper.  Whereas the first state of which only very few impressions survive) is set against a light background, the second state shows the portrait against a dark hatched background. The darker areas of shadow were also reduced.

Martin Luther's first version of the German translation of the New Testament appeared in September 1522 as a publication by the press established by Cranach and the goldsmith Christian Döring. Cranach and his assistant, who signed the last illustration with the monogram 'HB' (Hans Brosamer?), furnished the Apocalypse of St John with woodcuts [21], drawing heavily on Dürer`s series of the Apocalypse from 1498 [...]. titles.title: The Coach of Heaven and Hell by  Andreas Bodenstein, called Karlstadt

items.dimensions:
Sheet: 29.9 x 40.7 cm
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, No. 99]
items.description:
A correspondence lasting about two years between the Wittenberg theologian Andreas Bodenstein and the eminent scholar of Ingolstadt, Johannes Eck, preceded the publication of this woodcut. Only three specimens are known to have survived.  Following Luther's Theses from 31 October 1517 a theological discussion flared up, culminating in a public disputation that took place in Leipzig from the 27 June until the 15 July 1519. Prior to this disputation Karlstadt commissioned Cranach to produce this woodcut. The print polemically juxtaposes a theological stance based on Augustine and Paul, which shows the way to Christ (top, right to left), and a scholarly one, that leads directly into Hell (bottom, left to right). The message is reinforced by a large amount of text. The sheet marks the beginning of Cranach's Reformation propaganda and achieved its goal: Eck complained to the elector and the clergy in Leipzig tore it up on the pulpit and asked students in the confession box whether they had laughed. An impression of the print was also received by Albrecht Dürer in Nuremberg. 
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, 195, No. 99]

Cranach completed the 'Passional Christi und Antichristi' with 26 woodcut illustrations in March 1521 just before the Reichstag in Worms convened. This engraving served as the title-page to the second edition of the Wittenberg Heiligthumsbuch. This impression exhibits an impression of Cranach's woodcut of the church of All Saints printed on the verso (Hollstein, 96), but the book title in letter print has not survived.

Dürer's engraving served as the title-page of the Hallesche Heiligthumsbuch, published in Halle in 1520, and the designs of the woodcut illustrations in it by Dürer's pupil Wolf Traut were much influenced by Cranach's designs for the Wittenberg Heiligthumsbuch

items.dimensions:
Sheet: 34 x 23.5 cm
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, 206, No. 112]
items.description:
This sheet ranks among the few surviving early impressions of this woodcut that accurately reflect the rich detail and variety of the ambitious design. Cranach depicts St John the Baptist in a fur robe, standing opposite a crowd of listeners composed of people of every gender, age and social position, gathered under the electoral coat of arms. Some of the listeners wear contemporary dress and their facial expressions show true contrition. St John the Baptist was considered by Luther as a mediator between the old and new testaments.
[Exhib. Cat. Düsseldorf 2017, 206, No. 112]
